 3` and `a = b = 1`, `c = 2`. \n\n   Check pairs:\n   - `(1,1)`: Can take `S = {1}`\n   - `(1,2)`: `(1 + 2)/2 = 1.5`, need to find `S`:\n     - `{1}`: `1`\n     - `{2}`: `2`\n     - `{1,2}`: `sqrt(2)`\n     - `{1,1,2}`? No, `S` is a subset of indices, not values.\n     - Oh, no: `S` is a subset of `Fin 3`, which are indices `0, 1, 2`. So the deck is `[1, 1, 2]`. Then:\n       - `S = {0}`: `1`\n       - `S = {1}`: `1`\n       - `S = {2}`: `2`\n       - `S = {0,1}`: `1`\n       - `S = {0,2}`: `sqrt(2)`\n       - `S = {1,2}`: `sqrt(2)`\n       - `S = {0,1,2}`: `∛2 ≈ 1.26`\n     None of these equal `1.5`. \n\n   Hmm.\n\n   Another try: `n = 4`, `a = 1`, `a = 1`, `a = 1`, `a = 8`. \n\n   For `(1,8)`, `(1 + 8)/2 = 4.5`. Possible subsets:\n   - Any singleton: `1` or `8`\n   - `{1,1}`: `1`\n   - `{1,8}`: `sqrt(8) ≈ 2.828`\n   - `{1,1,8}`: `∛8 = 2`\n   - `{1,1,1,8}",
      "\n  exact by\n    apply Set.ext\n    intro n\n    simp only [Set.mem_setOf_eq]\n    <;>\n    (try decide) <;>\n    (try {\n      simp_all [answer]\n      <;>\n      aesop\n    }) <;>\n    (try {\n      cases n with\n      | zero => contradiction\n      | succ n =>\n        cases n with\n        | zero => contradiction\n        | succ n =>\n          simp_all [answer]\n          <;>\n          aesop\n    })",
      "\n  have h₁ : {n : ℕ | 1 < n ∧ ∀ (deck : Fin n → ℕ), (∀ i, 0 < deck i) → (Pairwise fun j k ↦ ∃ S : Finset (Fin n), S.Nonempty ∧ (deck j + deck k : ℝ) / 2 = (∏ i ∈ S, (deck i : ℝ)) ^ (1 / (#S : ℝ))) → ∀ i j, deck i = deck j} = {n : ℕ | 1 < n} := by\n    apply Set.ext\n    intro n\n    simp only [Set.mem_setOf_eq]\n    constructor\n    · -- Prove the forward direction: if n satisfies the condition, then 1 < n\n      intro h\n      exact h.1\n    · -- Prove the reverse direction: if 1 < n, then n satisfies the condition\n      intro h\n      have h₂ : 1 < n := h\n      constructor\n      · exact h₂\n      · -- Prove that for any deck, if the condition holds, then all deck entries are equal\n        intro deck hdeck_pos hdeck_pairwise\n        have h₃ : ∀ (i j : Fin n), deck i = deck j := by\n          -- Since the pairwise condition is strong enough to force all entries to be equal, we can directly use it\n          have h₄ : ∀ (i : Fin n), deck i = deck ⟨0, by\n            have h₅ : 0 < n := by linarith\n            omega\n          ⟩ := by\n            intro i\n            -- Use the fact that the pairwise condition implies all elements are equal\n            have h₅ : ∀ (j : Fin n), deck i = deck j := by\n              intro j\n              -- Use the given pairwise condition to deduce that all elements are equal\n              have h₆ : ∀ (i j : Fin n), deck i = deck j := by\n                intro i j\n                -- We need to show that deck i = deck j. We use the given condition to do this\n                have h₇ : Pairwise (fun j k => ∃ S : Finset (Fin n), S.Nonempty ∧ (deck j + deck k : ℝ) / 2 = (∏ i ∈ S, (deck i : ℝ)) ^ (1 / (#S : ℝ))) := hdeck_pairwise\n                -- Since the condition is pairwise, we can use it to deduce that all elements are equal\n                have h₈ : ∀ (i j : Fin n), deck i = deck j := by\n                  intro i j\n                  -- Use the given condition to deduce that all elements are equal\n              